                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d744">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.00/577: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-02-28T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 28, 1936—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>27. Your 44, February 28, noon, paragraph 2. I appreciate very much the high
                    sense of official responsibility and duty which you and your staff are
                    displaying during the present emergency situation; also the timely and helpful
                    telegrams which you are sending the Department. I realize that the information
                    contained in these telegrams has been difficult to obtain. We have complete
                    reliance upon the soundness of your judgment in deciding whether or not the
                    personnel of the Embassy should be temporarily transferred to a place removed
                    from the danger zone. You will of course keep in mind that we would not wish
                    that the Embassy staff be exposed unnecessarily to danger.</p>
                <p>Should any moves of persons or property be needed involving expenditures, a
                    special allowance will be granted upon telegraphic request therefor.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
